00:00:06.071 --> 00:00:09.428
Demand on your CARE: Presentation of illness symptoms in older adults

00:00:11.468 --> 00:00:13.994
Process of Healthy Ageing

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:20.924
From the moment we are born, our journey towards healthy ageing begins. 

00:00:20.924 --> 00:00:24.921
It all starts with the genes we inherit from our parents, 

00:00:24.921 --> 00:00:28.345
which play a role in determining how we age. 

00:00:29.129 --> 00:00:36.000
However, it's not just our genes that shape our health as we grow older. 

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.320
Our experiences in the womb influenced by and the subsequent environmental exposures 

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:43.764
and behaviour we are exposed to throughout our lives also have a significant impact.

00:00:44.784 --> 00:00:49.560
 In addition to these factors, we are also born into a social context. 

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:55.903
Some personal characteristics that are usually fixed, like our sex and ethnicity, 

00:00:55.903 --> 00:01:00.519
as well as those that can change or are influenced by societal norms, 

00:01:00.519 --> 00:01:06.000
such as our occupation, education, gender, or wealth will contribute to our social position in society, 

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.000
which affects the opportunities, barriers we face, as well as our access to resources.

00:01:12.779 --> 00:01:17.827
Unfortunately, these interactions can be unfair or inequitable. 

00:01:18.609 --> 00:01:24.373
The opportunities and resources we receive may not be based on our needs or rights,

00:01:24.373 --> 00:01:28.376
 but rather on our social or economic position. 

00:01:28.981 --> 00:01:35.522
This can lead to disparities in health and well-being among different individuals and communities.

00:01:36.571 --> 00:01:40.656
As we age, our bodies experience natural wear and tear. 

00:01:41.248 --> 00:01:44.815
There is a gradual accumulation of molecular and cellular damages, 

00:01:44.815 --> 00:01:47.372
leading to a general decline in our physiological reserves. 

00:01:47.372 --> 00:01:52.778
These physiological and homeostatic changes are largely inevitable, 

00:01:52.778 --> 00:01:59.836
although their extent can vary significantly from person to person at any particular chronological age. 

00:02:00.868 --> 00:02:07.336
Additionally, throughout our lives, we are exposed to a range of positive and negative environmental influences 

00:02:07.336 --> 00:02:12.668
that can further impact our health, such as physiological risk factors 

00:02:12.668 --> 00:02:19.146
(like high blood pressure), diseases, injuries, and broader geriatric syndromes. 

00:02:19.979 --> 00:02:25.446
The interaction of these health characteristics will ultimately determine our intrinsic capacity, 

00:02:25.446 --> 00:02:30.000
which encompasses all our physical and mental capacities. 

00:02:30.361 --> 00:02:37.359
However, whether older people can achieve the things that they value will not be determined just by this capacity 

00:02:37.359 --> 00:02:42.998
but also by further interactions with the environments they inhabit at a particular point in time.

00:02:43.555 --> 00:02:50.737
On the other hand, our functional ability is a result of the interaction between ourselves and the environment we inhabit. 

00:02:51.262 --> 00:02:55.532
Therefore, healthy ageing is a multidimensional process 

00:02:55.532 --> 00:03:02.754
influenced by genetics, lifestyle choices, and social, economic, and environmental factors. 

00:03:02.754 --> 00:03:07.880
Since your current state of health is often the outcome of your previous life experiences, 

00:03:07.880 --> 00:03:11.658
even though we may face many irreversible factors, 

00:03:11.658 --> 00:03:15.750
we can establish healthy lifestyles early on, 

00:03:15.750 --> 00:03:23.006
such as a healthy diet, regular exercise, and stress management, to counteract the effects of ageing.

00:03:23.801 --> 00:03:27.195
 To learn more about it, let’s watch our video 

00:03:27.195 --> 00:03:29.849
“10 Tips for Healthy Ageing”.

